==Old English==
===Pronunciation===
[[IPA]]: /jæaɹd/
===Etymology===
Common Germanic *''[[gardaz]]'', from Indo-European ''*ghardh-'' ‘yard, court’.  Cognate with Old Frisian ''garda'', Old Saxon ''gardo'' (Dutch ''[[gaard]]''), Old High German ''[[gart]]'' (German ''[[Garten]]''), Old Norse ''[[garðr]]'' (Icelandic ''[[garður]]'', Swedish ''[[gård]]''), Gothic [[𐌲𐌰𐍂𐌳𐌰]], [[𐌲𐌰𐍂𐌳𐍃]].  The IE root is also the source of Common Slavic *''[[gord]]'' (Old Church Slavonic [[градъ]], Russian [[город]] ‘town’), Albanian ''[[gardh]]'' ‘fence’.
===Noun===
'''ġeard''' ''m''
# an [[enclosure]], an enclosed place; a [[yard]], a [[garden]], [[dwelling]], a [[court]], a [[region]] or [[land]]
#:''Brade synd on worulde grene geardas'': in the world are broad green regions.
===Descendants===
*English [[yard]]
